Sender  Suzuran~
Date    Tue Apr 16 06:40:31 2002~
Stamp   1018957231
To      all~
Subject Changes...~
Text
These are for imms really, but I guess I'll send this to all for the
hell of it.

1) act() works for mobiles again.  Switching should work normally.

2) We have a signal handler now; It catches on SIGSEGV at the moment.
Upon catching SEGV, it takes a snapshot-coredump of ROM.  This is done
by fork()ing a second copy of ROM and calling abort().  When you loook
at the stack backtrace in the corefile, the frame that caused the crash
will be the one immediately before the call to sigaction().  Here's an
example backtrace:

#0  0x400624c1 in kill () from /lib/libc.so.6
#1  0x4006212a in raise () from /lib/libc.so.6
#2  0x400636ff in abort () from /lib/libc.so.6
#3  0x806e4b3 in segv_handler (svx=11, siginfo=0x0, fnord=0xbfffc250)
at comm.c:3298
#4  0x400623d0 in sigaction () from /lib/libc.so.6
#5  0x40095a7b in vsprintf () from /lib/libc.so.6
*** THE CRASH HAPPENED HERE IN VSPRINTF ***
(rest of stack backtrace snipped)

After dropping core, the handler goes into a loop handling players
one at a time.  First it sends them a message explaining what has
happened, then tries to save their pfile in ../crash/Character.
If this works, it saves normally, and goes to the next character,
until it causes another SIGSEGV or saves all connected players.
On a double-SEGV rom will exit immediately.  Otherwise, once all
players have been saved, ROM will reboot.

What I would *LIKE* to do is cause the function that caused the crash
to return() from the signal handler and thus continue the MUD and avoid
the reboot entirely.  This involves having your program manipulate it's
own stack frames; Does anyone know how to do this?
I know how to do it in assembly but I don't know how to do it in C.

Suzuran Majere
~
